and the vertical axis is the profitability.

7
00:00:21,640 --> 00:00:23,890
And we said there were two regions.

8
00:00:23,890 --> 00:00:27,760
Regions here to the left is when I ordered too little,

9
00:00:27,760 --> 00:00:32,220
and that means I might be short some products.

10
00:00:32,220 --> 00:00:35,810
And to the right is when I ordered too much,

11
00:00:35,810 --> 00:00:40,690
and there's a higher probability I'll have excess.

12
00:00:40,690 --> 00:00:44,660
And so what we want to do is figure out how can I find that

13
00:00:44,660 --> 00:00:47,020
Q*.

14
00:00:47,020 --> 00:00:50,380
So for Single Period Problems we have two costs.

15
00:00:50,380 --> 00:00:52,110
We have this Excess Cost.

16
00:00:52,110 --> 00:00:56,080
And this happens when the demand is less than what I wanted,

17
00:00:56,080 --> 00:01:02,500
than Q. And so this means I have too much product.

18
00:01:02,500 --> 00:01:04,849
And so for this is going to be, when

19
00:01:04,849 --> 00:01:07,300
I have too much laying around, I have Excess.

20
00:01:07,300 --> 00:01:10,200
Then I've also got the Shortage Cost, when the demand is

21
00:01:10,200 --> 00:01:12,440
greater than Q for whatever I pick,

22
00:01:12,440 --> 00:01:14,510
and that's having too little product,

23
00:01:14,510 --> 00:01:16,730
and I'm not going to have enough there.

24
00:01:16,730 --> 00:01:18,010
So what do I want to do?

25
00:01:18,010 --> 00:01:20,810
Well, I've got a continuous distribution of demand.

26
00:01:20,810 --> 00:01:25,360
So I'm going to be able to find what is the Expected Excess

27
00:01:25,360 --> 00:01:26,830
Costs for the Qth unit.

28
00:01:26,830 --> 00:01:28,965
This is the marginal cost, that next unit

29
00:01:28,965 --> 00:01:30,090
that's going to be ordered.

30
00:01:30,090 --> 00:01:32,350
Well, what is that going to be?

31
00:01:32,350 --> 00:01:35,462
It's going to be equal to that cost of being excess.

32
00:01:35,462 --> 00:01:37,670
And we already figured out what that's going to be --

33
00:01:37,670 --> 00:01:41,850
it's the cost of having an extra one times the probability that

34
00:01:41,850 --> 00:01:43,870
my demand is less than or equal to Q.

35
00:01:43,870 --> 00:01:46,850
So that's the Expected Excess Cost for that Qth order.

36
00:01:46,850 --> 00:01:50,120
And I can do the same thing for the shortage cost of the Qth

37
00:01:50,120 --> 00:01:50,950
order.

38
00:01:50,950 --> 00:01:54,730
That's Q_s times 1 minus that probability.

39
00:01:54,730 --> 00:01:58,560
And so what I have here are the two costs, the marginal costs,

40
00:01:58,560 --> 00:02:02,440
for having too little and having too much.

41
00:02:02,440 --> 00:02:07,350
And, you know, if my Excess Cost is less than my Shortage Cost,

42
00:02:07,350 --> 00:02:09,914
I'm just going to increase my Q. How much am I

43
00:02:09,914 --> 00:02:11,420
going to increase my Q?

44
00:02:11,420 --> 00:02:14,270
Well, I'm going to increase it until they're equal,

45
00:02:14,270 --> 00:02:17,440
because, essentially, I'm going to climb the hill,

46
00:02:17,440 --> 00:02:21,140
climb it up until the slope is 0.

47
00:02:21,140 --> 00:02:23,030
Think back to calculus.

48
00:02:23,030 --> 00:02:26,670
And so where the marginal costs are the same,

49
00:02:26,670 --> 00:02:29,372
that's where my maximum is going to be.

50
00:02:29,372 --> 00:02:31,580
So let's look at this in terms of the marginal costs.

51
00:02:31,580 --> 00:02:32,871
So what I have here is a chart.

52
00:02:32,871 --> 00:02:36,990
Again, the horizontal axis is the Q.

53
00:02:36,990 --> 00:02:40,610
And this is the marginal cost per jersey:

54
00:02:40,610 --> 00:02:42,560
that's the vertical axis.

55
00:02:42,560 --> 00:02:48,590
And so if I look at this blue line, which is the Excess Cost:

56
00:02:48,590 --> 00:02:52,440
this is the marginal increase, or the marginal cost,

57
00:02:52,440 --> 00:02:53,790
for being excess.

58
00:02:53,790 --> 00:02:58,240
So if I only order 10, and, remember, my distribution here

59
00:02:58,240 --> 00:03:01,585
was distributed normally with the demand of 32,

60
00:03:01,585 --> 00:03:04,020
with the standard deviation of 11.

61
00:03:04,020 --> 00:03:07,810
We're in units of thousands -- 32,000 units with the standard

62
00:03:07,810 --> 00:03:09,140
deviation of 11,000.

63
00:03:09,140 --> 00:03:13,740
If I ordered 10,000 units here, then the probability

64
00:03:13,740 --> 00:03:16,370
that I'm going to have excess is pretty low.

65
00:03:16,370 --> 00:03:18,180
That means there would have to be

66
00:03:18,180 --> 00:03:22,750
9,999 units demanded or less, right?

67
00:03:22,750 --> 00:03:24,780
So it'd be pretty low.

68
00:03:24,780 --> 00:03:26,580
As I get up and order a higher amount,

69
00:03:26,580 --> 00:03:30,200
if I order 60,000 units, the probability

70
00:03:30,200 --> 00:03:33,250
of me getting excess, of having excess jerseys lying around,

71
00:03:33,250 --> 00:03:36,470
gets pretty high, and so the marginal cost increases.

72
00:03:36,470 --> 00:03:39,040
And you see how it changes and it's not linear.

73
00:03:39,040 --> 00:03:42,470
And that's a reflection of the underlying normal distribution.

74
00:03:42,470 --> 00:03:45,850
I can also plot in red these Shortage Costs.

75
00:03:45,850 --> 00:03:50,380
And again, we can look, if I ordered only 10,000 jerseys,

76
00:03:50,380 --> 00:03:53,460
when my expected amount is 32,000,

77
00:03:53,460 --> 00:03:55,679
then I'm going to have a pretty high marginal cost,

78
00:03:55,679 --> 00:03:57,220
because I expect it to be very short.

79
00:03:57,220 --> 00:04:01,290
I'm going to be short a bunch if I expect on average 32,000

80
00:04:01,290 --> 00:04:03,270
and I only order 10,000.

81
00:04:03,270 --> 00:04:06,580
But at the other extreme, if I order 60,000,

82
00:04:06,580 --> 00:04:09,790
then chances are I'm not going to be short anymore.

83
00:04:09,790 --> 00:04:12,060
And so you see that these two marginal costs

84
00:04:12,060 --> 00:04:13,550
work in opposite directions.

85
00:04:13,550 --> 00:04:15,200
And when are they equal?

86
00:04:15,200 --> 00:04:19,060
Well, that's our optimal Q, because when they're

87
00:04:19,060 --> 00:04:20,899
equal to each other, then that means

88
00:04:20,899 --> 00:04:23,920
I'm at the maximum of that profit curve.

89
00:04:23,920 --> 00:04:28,220
And so that tells me my Q*.

