105
00:05:08,390 --> 00:05:12,250
It's just a ratio of shortage over the total of the Excess

106
00:05:12,250 --> 00:05:13,217
and Shortage Cost.

107
00:05:13,217 --> 00:05:15,550
So let's see if we can talk about that just a little bit

108
00:05:15,550 --> 00:05:16,510
more.

109
00:05:16,510 --> 00:05:19,110
Think of it like a seesaw.

110
00:05:19,110 --> 00:05:24,800
And on the one end, I've got my cost of being excess.

111
00:05:24,800 --> 00:05:28,050
And at my other end, sitting at the other end of the seesaw

112
00:05:28,050 --> 00:05:31,510
is the cost of being short.

113
00:05:31,510 --> 00:05:33,500
And so the question is where do I

114
00:05:33,500 --> 00:05:37,310
put the fulcrum to make it balanced?

115
00:05:37,310 --> 00:05:40,650
We can think of this distance from the fulcrum

116
00:05:40,650 --> 00:05:44,970
to c_e as being equal to the Critical Ratio, which

117
00:05:44,970 --> 00:05:53,030
is c_s / (c_e + c_s), just this term, right?

118
00:05:53,030 --> 00:05:59,660
So if one case, what if c_e = c_s, where will the fulcrum be?

119
00:05:59,660 --> 00:06:02,480
Right in the middle, right in the middle,

120
00:06:02,480 --> 00:06:04,090
as you have half and half.

121
00:06:04,090 --> 00:06:10,690
But what happens if say, c_s is equal to twice as much as c_e,

122
00:06:10,690 --> 00:06:12,800
so much Shortage Cost is twice as much

123
00:06:12,800 --> 00:06:14,590
as if I have Excess Cost.

124
00:06:14,590 --> 00:06:16,540
Well, what's our critical ratio going to be?

125
00:06:16,540 --> 00:06:18,730
I can just plug this in.

126
00:06:18,730 --> 00:06:22,580
So it's 2c_e / 3 c_e, it's going to mean

127
00:06:22,580 --> 00:06:27,160
that the critical ratio is 2/3.

128
00:06:27,160 --> 00:06:29,540
So what's going to happen to that fulcrum?

129
00:06:29,540 --> 00:06:33,930
It's going to move 2/3 of the way there, so my fulcrum here.

130
00:06:33,930 --> 00:06:34,970
Because what happened?

131
00:06:34,970 --> 00:06:37,710
This got twice as heavy, this became the big guy,

132
00:06:37,710 --> 00:06:40,450
sitting in there's a little guy half the size over here.

133
00:06:40,450 --> 00:06:47,780
So as my c_s gets bigger, my cost of being short,

134
00:06:47,780 --> 00:06:52,680
my Critical Ratio gets bigger, and it moves closer to that.

135
00:06:52,680 --> 00:06:55,320
So just like a seesaw, you could look at the other way

136
00:06:55,320 --> 00:06:58,090
if c_e get got really big in proportion to c_s,

137
00:06:58,090 --> 00:07:00,200
then the fulcrum would move the other way.

138
00:07:00,200 --> 00:07:01,920
So you can think of it as just a balance.

139
00:07:01,920 --> 00:07:04,780
Where's the balance between the two?

140
00:07:04,780 --> 00:07:08,040
Now, if I look at the left side of this equation,

141
00:07:08,040 --> 00:07:10,340
the probability x is less than or equal to Q,

142
00:07:10,340 --> 00:07:12,230
you should be able to remember what that is,

143
00:07:12,230 --> 00:07:16,220
thinking back to our beloved normal curve.

144
00:07:16,220 --> 00:07:19,160
That's my best estimation of a normal curve.

145
00:07:19,160 --> 00:07:22,620
And I've got some mean demand here.

146
00:07:22,620 --> 00:07:25,370
Then what I'm saying is this probability

147
00:07:25,370 --> 00:07:27,790
that x is less than or equal to Q

148
00:07:27,790 --> 00:07:32,970
is simply this area under the curve, where this is Q.

149
00:07:32,970 --> 00:07:35,790
And so this is that.

150
00:07:35,790 --> 00:07:40,140
So what happens as the Critical Ratio --

151
00:07:40,140 --> 00:07:41,820
right here I said this is the example,

152
00:07:41,820 --> 00:07:45,170
where the Cost of Shortage is equal to twice the Cost

153
00:07:45,170 --> 00:07:45,920
of Excess.

154
00:07:45,920 --> 00:07:48,550
So the Critical Ratio is 2/3.

155
00:07:48,550 --> 00:07:51,240
As this Critical Ratio gets bigger, what happens?

156
00:07:51,240 --> 00:07:53,030
This Q is going to have to get bigger,

157
00:07:53,030 --> 00:07:58,120
because I have to cover -- let's see -- this amount.

158
00:07:58,120 --> 00:08:01,000
I would have to make that amount of the probability out there

159
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:04,650
is equal to 2/3.

160
00:08:04,650 --> 00:08:08,090
So the lesson here is as the Critical Ratio

161
00:08:08,090 --> 00:08:11,440
gets bigger, which means the Cost of Shortage is increasing,

162
00:08:11,440 --> 00:08:14,460
then I've got to cover more of my demand distribution.

163
00:08:14,460 --> 00:08:15,450
That's all that means.

164
00:08:15,450 --> 00:08:17,050
We're looking at normal curve now,

165
00:08:17,050 --> 00:08:19,300
but we'll look at other distributions later.

166
00:08:19,300 --> 00:08:22,690
All it means is a need to cover that percentage

167
00:08:22,690 --> 00:08:27,060
or that probability of that demand happening to be optimal.

